<html>
<title>Intro. to CD Ranking Book -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><center>
<h2><i>Introduction to the Congressional Ranking Book</i></h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%>
</center>
For specific questions, email:<br>
<a href="mailto:dwinston@dgs.dgsys.com">David H. Winston</a>, Senior Fellow For Statistical Policy Analysis<br>
<a href="mailto:olsonc@heritage.org">Christine L. Olson</a>, Policy Analyst, Economics<br>
<a href="mailto:hedermanr@heritage.org">Rea S. Hederman</a>, Research Analyst<br>
<p>
As members of Congress consider legislative proposals that will lead us into the next century, it is important that we understand the demographic composition of the districts they represent. This book does just that. We have used 1990 Long Form Census information, and ranked the Congressional Districts in numerous key categories, including the total amount of public assistance districts get, the total amount of farm income, the number of people who have a mortgage, just to name a few. In all we have 97 different categories to look at.<p>The layout of these reports is straightforward. <p>



<pre>
              People Over 65 -- Percent
       Congressional District Average:	12.5%

		State	CD	%	Deviation

	1.	FL	22	31.1%	5.49
	2.	FL	13	30.9%	5.44
	3.	FL	19	28.1%	4.62
	4.	FL	10	26.2%	4.03
	5.	FL	05	25.7%	3.88
	6.	FL	14	25.6%	3.87
	7.	FL	16	23.9%	3.36
	8.	FL	09	21.7%	2.70
	9.	AZ	03	19.7%	2.13

</pre>





<ul><li>The ranking is simply where the Congressional District is in relation to the other 434 and the District of Columbia.<p><li>The CD identifies each district with the two letter state abbreviation, and the Congressional District number within the state. 
<p>
<li>The # or % is the actual information. For example, the % of Asians in a district.
<p>
<li>The deviation is a little more complex. This is to show how far from the average a particular district is. It answers the question of whether the district is just slightly different from the national average, or significantly different. It also allows you to see the difference between two districts more clearly as well. 
<p>
<li>For more information on the U.S. Census Bureau, visit their web page, at <a href="http://www.census.gov/">http://www.census.gov/</a>

</ul><p>
We hope this book will give readers a better understanding of all the Congressional Districts and what issues members might be concerned about. 
<p>
For specific questions, or comments, email:<br>
<a href="mailto:dwinston@dgs.dgsys.com">David H. Winston</a>, Senior Fellow For Statistical Policy Analysis<br>
<a href="mailto:olsonc@heritage.org">Christine L. Olson</a>, Policy Analyst<br>
<a href="mailto:hedermanr@heritage.org">Rea S. Hederman</a>, Research Analyst<br><p><p>
Go to the <a href="i-cdrank.html">Ranking Book</a>
<p><center>

<A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map">
<IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></body></html>
</center>
